            <!-- AUTOPSY SLIDE 1: Introduction -->
            <section>
                <h2>1. Autopsy: The Foundation</h2>
                <div class="col-container">
                    <div class="col">
                        <h4 style="color:#fff">What is it?</h4>
                        <p>Autopsy is the premier open-source digital forensics platform. It serves as a graphical interface (GUI) for <strong>The Sleuth Kit (TSK)</strong>.</p>
                        <p>It allows investigators to analyze hard drives, smartphones, and media cards efficiently without typing commands.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col ui-box">
                        <h4 style="color:#fff; border-bottom: 1px solid #555; padding-bottom:5px;">Key Specs</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 0.9em; list-style: none; margin: 0;">
                            <li>✅ <strong>License:</strong> Apache 2.0 (Free)</li>
                            <li>✅ <strong>OS:</strong> Windows, Linux, macOS</li>
                            <li>✅ <strong>Target:</strong> Law Enforcement, Corp Security</li>
                            <li>✅ <strong>Input:</strong> E01, Raw (dd), VMDK</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AUTOPSY SLIDE 2: The Interface -->
            <section>
                <h2>2. The Interface</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 0.8em;">The 3-Pane Layout maximizes efficiency.</p>
                
                <div class="col-container" style="align-items: stretch; height: 350px;">
                    <!-- Pane 1 -->
                    <div class="ui-box" style="flex: 1; border-top: 3px solid #00d4ff;">
                        <strong style="color: #00d4ff;">1. Tree Viewer</strong>
                        <hr style="border-color: #444;">
                        <ul style="font-size: 0.8em; line-height: 2;">
                            <li>Data Sources</li>
                            <li>File Views</li>
                            <li>Tags</li>
                            <li>Results</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Panes 2 & 3 -->
                    <div style="flex: 3; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px;">
                        <div class="ui-box" style="flex: 1; border-top: 3px solid #ff5e5e;">
                            <strong style="color: #ff5e5e;">2. Result Viewer</strong><br>
                            <span style="font-size: 0.8em">Top right pane. Lists files in the selected folder. Shows name, time, size, hash, and match score.</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="ui-box" style="flex: 1; border-top: 3px solid #0f0;">
                            <strong style="color: #0f0;">3. Content Viewer</strong><br>
                            <span style="font-size: 0.8em">Bottom right pane. The "Inspector". Shows Hex, Strings, Metadata, and Images.</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AUTOPSY SLIDE 3: Ingest Modules -->
            <section>
                <h2>3. Ingest Modules</h2>
                <p>The automated "Engine" of Autopsy that processes data.</p>
                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">
                    <div class="ui-box">
                        <span class="highlight">Recent Activity</span><br>
                        Extracts web history, cookies, and downloads from Chrome/Edge/Firefox.
                    </div>
                    <div class="ui-box">
                        <span class="highlight">Hash Lookup</span><br>
                        Identifies "Known Good" files (NSRL) to hide them, and "Known Bad" files to flag them.
                    </div>
                    <div class="ui-box">
                        <span class="highlight">File Type Id</span><br>
                        Ignores extensions. Finds a JPEG even if it's named <code>system.dll</code> using Magic Numbers.
                    </div>
                    <div class="ui-box">
                        <span class="highlight">Keyword Search</span><br>
                        Indexes all text on the drive using <strong>Solr</strong> for instant Google-like searching.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AUTOPSY SLIDE 4: Advanced Features -->
            <section>
                <h2>4. Advanced Capabilities</h2>
                <div class="col-container">
                    <div class="col ui-box">
                        <h4>Timeline Analysis</h4>
                        <p>Visualizes system events in a graphical bar chart. Helps answer: <em>"What happened last Tuesday at 2 PM?"</em></p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col ui-box">
                        <h4>Central Repository</h4>
                        <p>Correlates data across cases. If a USB drive appears in <em>Case A</em> and later in <em>Case B</em>, Autopsy alerts you.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col ui-box">
                        <h4>Android Analyzer</h4>
                        <p>Parses SQLite DBs from Android backups to recover SMS, Call Logs, and Contacts.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AUTOPSY SLIDE 5: Reporting & Workflow -->
            <section>
                <h2>5. Reporting & Triage</h2>
                <ul style="font-size: 0.9em;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>HTML Reports:</strong> Easy-to-read, navigable reports for clients, lawyers, or HR.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Excel/CASE Reports:</strong> Structured data output for importing into other tools.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Triage Mode:</strong> Run Autopsy from a USB stick on a live computer to preview files before seizure.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Tagging:</strong> Bookmark specific files (e.g., "Evidence 001") and add comments for the final report.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>


            <!-- =========================
                 EXIFTOOL SECTION (2 Slides)
                 ========================= -->

            <!-- EXIFTOOL SLIDE 1: Intro -->
            <section>
                <h2>ExifTool: The Metadata King</h2>
                <h4 style="color: #ff5e5e;">Beyond the Image</h4>
                <div class="col-container">
                    <div class="col">
                        <p>ExifTool is a command-line application (CLI) for reading, writing, and editing meta information.</p>
                        <p>It sees what the operating system hides.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col">
                         <div class="cmd-box">
> Camera Model : iPhone 13 Pro
> GPS Position : 40 deg 42' N
> Software     : Adobe Photoshop 24.1
> Create Date  : 2023:11:05 14:22:10
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="ui-box" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                    <strong style="color:#00d4ff">Forensic Value:</strong> Reveals camera serial numbers, lens models, editing software traces, and original creation timestamps.
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- EXIFTOOL SLIDE 2: Commands -->
            <section>
                <h2>Tactical Commands</h2>
                <p>Essential one-liners for the investigator.</p>
                
                <div class="cmd-box">
# 1. Standard Extraction
$ exiftool evidence.jpg

# 2. The "Deep Dive" (Show duplicates & unknown tags)
$ exiftool -a -u -g1 evidence.jpg

# 3. Privacy Scrub (Remove all GPS tags)
$ exiftool -gps:all= suspect_photo.jpg

# 4. Generate CSV Report for entire folder
$ exiftool -common -csv images_folder > report.csv
                </div>
                <br>
                <p><small style="color: #ff5e5e;">Pro Tip: The <code>-g1</code> flag is critical. It groups tags by location (IFD0, ExifIFD, GPS) to reveal exactly where data is stored.</small></p>
            </section>

            <!-- SLIDE: Conclusion -->
            <section>
                <h2>Summary</h2>
                <div class="col-container">
                    <div class="col ui-box" style="border-top: 4px solid #00d4ff;">
                        <h3 style="color:#fff">Autopsy</h3>
                        <p><strong>The Macro Tool</strong></p>
                        <p>Use it to manage the case, index the drive, and find the relevant files.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col ui-box" style="border-top: 4px solid #ff5e5e;">
                        <h3 style="color:#fff">ExifTool</h3>
                        <p><strong>The Micro Tool</strong></p>
                        <p>Use it to surgically extract hidden metadata from specific files found by Autopsy.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

